window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>1","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CLASSIFICATION","question":"The Genus into which man is classified is","images":[],"options":{"A":"Chordata","B":"Mammalia","C":"Homo","D":"Sapiens"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The genus into which man is classified is 'Homo'. In biological classification, the genus is a rank in the hierarchy of taxonomy that is one level above species. The full scientific name for humans is Homo sapiens, where 'Homo' is the genus.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>2","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : LIFE CYCLES","question":"The diagram below is an illustration of the nymph of an insect. Study it and answer the question below      The organism illustrated is a stage in the development of","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"grasshopper","B":"mosquito","C":"termite","D":"cockroach"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The nymph is the immature stage of insects that undergo incomplete metamorphosis (also called hemimetabolous development).","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>3","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : GROWTH","question":"The diagram below is an illustration of the nymph of an insect. Study it and answer the question below    The growth process that would occur in the organism before it becomes an adult is","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"respiration","B":"locomotion","C":"moulting","D":"sensitivity"},"answer":"C","explanation":"For a nymph (like in cockroach), the growth process it must undergo before becoming an adult is moulting (ecdysis).  Insects with incomplete metamorphosis grow by repeatedly shedding their exoskeleton as they increase in size.    This shedding process is called moulting or ecdysis.    After each moult, the nymph looks more like the adult, and with the final moult it develops fully formed wings and reproductive organs.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>4","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : PLANT STRUCTURE","question":"The diagram below is an illustration of a dicot leaf. Study it and answer the question      The parts labelled I, II, III and IV respectively are","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"veins, apex, midrib, stalk","B":"midrib, petiole, margin, stalk","C":"apex, lamina, blade, axil","D":"apex, midrib, lamina, axil"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Apex    The tip or end of the leaf, opposite the petiole (leaf stalk).    It can be pointed, rounded, notched, or other shapes depending on the plant.    2. Midrib    The central/main vein of the leaf.    It runs from the base (near the petiole) to the apex.    Provides support and helps in the transport of water, minerals, and food.    3. Lamina (Leaf blade)    The broad, flat surface of the leaf.    It is the main site of photosynthesis because it contains many chloroplasts.    It also helps in transpiration and gas exchange.    4. Axil    The angle formed between the upper side of a leaf/branch and the stem.    Usually contains a bud (axillary bud) that can grow into a new shoot or flower.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>5","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : PLANT STRUCTURE","question":"The diagram below is an illustration of a dicot leaf. Study it and answer the question    The part that contains the phloem and xylem is labelled","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"I","B":"II","C":"III","D":"IV"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Xylem \u2192 transports water and mineral salts from the roots to the leaves.    Phloem \u2192 transports manufactured food (sugar, amino acids, etc.) from the leaves to other parts of the plant.    Together, they form the vascular tissue system, usually arranged in vascular bundles inside stems, roots, and leaves.    In a leaf, the midrib and veins contain the vascular bundles","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>6","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CELL STRUCTURE AND FUNCTIONS OF CELL COMPONENTS.","question":"The functions of vacuoles in plants are storage and","images":[],"options":{"A":"protection","B":"strength","C":"support","D":"sensitivity"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The functions of vacuoles in plants include storage and protection. Vacuoles are membrane-bound organelles that store nutrients, waste products, and help maintain turgor pressure in plant cells, which is essential for structural support.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>7","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CELL STRUCTURE AND FUNCTIONS OF CELL COMPONENTS.","question":"Four cells each with osmotic potential of about 3% salt solution were immersed respectively into solutions of different concentrations as follows.  I- 1% salt solution  II- 3% salt solution  III- 6% salt solution  IV- 10% salt solution  Use the information to answer the question below    Which of the solutions would cause an increase in osmotic pressure within the cell?","images":[],"options":{"A":"I","B":"II","C":"III","D":"IV"},"answer":"C","explanation":"An increase in osmotic pressure within the cell occurs when the cell is placed in a solution with a higher concentration of solutes than its own. In this case, solution III (6% salt solution) has a higher concentration than the 3% salt solution of the cells, leading to water moving into the cell and increasing osmotic pressure.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>8","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CELL AND ITS ENVIRONMENT","question":"Four cells each with osmotic potential of about 3% salt solution were immersed respectively into solutions of different concentrations as follows.  I- 1% salt solution  II- 3% salt solution  III- 6% salt solution  IV- 10% salt solution  Use the information to answer the question below  If the cells are plant cells, what would happen to the cell in solution III? It would become","images":[],"options":{"A":"turgid","B":"crenated","C":"haemolysed","D":"plasmolysed"},"answer":"D","explanation":"If the plant cells are placed in solution III (6% salt solution), which has a higher concentration of solutes than the cells' internal environment (3% salt solution), the cells would lose water and undergo plasmolysis. Plasmolysis is the process where the cell membrane pulls away from the cell wall due to loss of water.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>9","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ENERGY TRANSFORMATION IN NATURE","question":"How many molecules of oxygen are required for the aerobic respiration of three molecules of glucose?","images":[],"options":{"A":"3","B":"6","C":"12","D":"18"},"answer":"D","explanation":"For the aerobic respiration of glucose, the general equation is C6H12O6 + 6O2 \u2192 6CO2 + 6H2O.   1 molecule of glucose requires 6 molecules of oxygen.  Therefore, for three molecules of glucose, the equation would be 3C6H12O6 + 18O2 \u2192 18CO2 + 18H2O. . Thus, 18 molecules of oxygen are required for the aerobic respiration of three molecules of glucose.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>10","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : TISSUES AND SUPPORTING SYSTEMS","question":"Sclerenchyma tissue in plants is for","images":[],"options":{"A":"water conduction","B":"mechanical support","C":"food storage","D":"food transport"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Sclerenchyma tissue in plants provides mechanical support due to its thickened cell walls, which are often lignified. This tissue is important for maintaining the structural integrity of plants, especially in areas that require strength.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>11","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CELL STRUCTURE AND FUNCTIONS OF CELL COMPONENTS.","question":"The diagram below is an illustration of a cell carrying out a biological process. Study it and answer the question below.      The process is referred to as","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"phagocytosis","B":"pinocytosis","C":"endocytosis","D":"exocytosis"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The process by which a cell engulfs bacteria is called phagocytosis.  Phagocytosis is a type of endocytosis (\"cell eating\").    The cell membrane surrounds and engulfs large particles like bacteria, forming a phagosome.    The phagosome then fuses with lysosomes, which release enzymes to digest and destroy the bacteria.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>12","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : ORGANIZATION OF LIFE","question":"The diagram below is an illustration of a cell carrying out a biological process. Study it and answer the question below.    The biological system that contains cells that carry out the illustrated biological process in humans is","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"reproduction","B":"circulatory","C":"respiratory","D":"nervous"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The biological system in humans that contains cells which carry out this process is the immune system (specifically, the circulatory system/blood where white blood cells are found).","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>13","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : LIFE CYCLES","question":"Which of the following statements is not correct about respiration in plants?","images":[],"options":{"A":"It occurs in all plant tissues","B":"Light and chlorophyll must be present for it to occur","C":"Energy is produced as the end product","D":"It occurs in the presence of oxygen"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The statement 'Light and chlorophyll must be present for it to occur' is not correct about respiration in plants. Respiration is a metabolic process that occurs in all plant tissues and does not require light or chlorophyll, as it primarily involves the breakdown of glucose to produce energy.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>14","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : EXCRETORY SYSTEMS","question":"Urine, when compared with blood in mammals is hypertonic because","images":[],"options":{"A":"urine contains high percentage of all cells","B":"all traces of sugar have been removed from urine","C":"urea is actively secreted into the renal tubules","D":"much water has been removed from urine"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Urine is hypertonic compared to blood because much water has been removed from urine during the filtration and reabsorption processes in the kidneys. This results in a higher concentration of solutes, such as urea, in urine compared to blood.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>15","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : HORMONAL COORDINATION","question":"The naturally produced auxin in plants is","images":[],"options":{"A":"indole acetic acid","B":"dichlorophenoxyacetic acid","C":"aldone","D":"florigen"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The naturally produced auxin in plants is indole acetic acid (IAA). Auxins are a class of plant hormones that play a crucial role in regulating growth and development, including cell elongation and response to light.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>16","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : NERVOUS COORDINATION","question":"The sympathetic nervous system causes","images":[],"options":{"A":"constriction of the arteries","B":"heartbeat to slow down","C":"increase in the secretion of saliva","D":"contraction of the bladder"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The sympathetic nervous system is responsible for the 'fight or flight' response, which includes the constriction of arteries to redirect blood flow to essential organs and muscles. This response increases heart rate and decreases non-essential functions, such as saliva secretion.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>17","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : SENSE ORGANS","question":"Long sightedness could be corrected using a","images":[],"options":{"A":"biconvex lens","B":"convex lens","C":"biconcave lens","D":"concave lens"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Long sightedness, or hyperopia, is a condition where distant objects can be seen clearly, but close ones do not come into proper focus. This condition can be corrected using a biconvex lens, which converges light rays before they enter the eye, allowing the image to be focused on the retina. The correct option is 'biconvex lens'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>18","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : SENSE ORGANS","question":"During the process of hearing in mammals, the structure in the middle ear which receives the first vibration is the","images":[],"options":{"A":"oval window","B":"round window","C":"incus","D":"malleus"},"answer":"D","explanation":"In the process of hearing, the malleus (also known as the hammer) is the first bone in the middle ear that receives vibrations from the eardrum. It transmits these vibrations to the incus and then to the stapes, which ultimately leads to the oval window. Therefore, the correct option is 'malleus'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>19","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : HABITATS","question":"An important characteristic of fruits dispersed by water is the presence of","images":[],"options":{"A":"fibrous covering","B":"smooth surface","C":"water content","D":"pericarp"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Fruits that are dispersed by water typically have a fibrous covering that helps them float. This adaptation allows them to be carried by water currents to new locations where they can germinate. Thus, the correct option is 'fibrous covering'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>20","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : LIFE CYCLES","question":"Plants which grow and produce fruits within a year are called","images":[],"options":{"A":"biennials","B":"perennials","C":"annuals","D":"herbs"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Plants that grow and produce fruits within a year are classified as annuals. They complete their life cycle, from germination to seed production, within a single growing season. Therefore, the correct option is 'annuals'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>21","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : MODES OF NUTRITION","question":"Chemical digestion in organisms is the","images":[],"options":{"A":"breakdown of starch into carbohydrates","B":"breakdown of complex molecules into simple molecules","C":"build up of simple insoluble molecules into complex soluble molecules","D":"build up of simple soluble molecules into complex insoluble molecules"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Chemical digestion refers to the process of breaking down complex molecules into simpler molecules, which can be absorbed by the body. This process involves enzymes that catalyze the breakdown of food substances. Therefore, the correct option is 'breakdown of complex molecules into simple molecules'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>22","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : NUTRIENT CYCLING IN NATURE","question":"Excessive bleeding from an injury could be due to the lack of vitamin","images":[],"options":{"A":"K","B":"E","C":"B","D":"A"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Excessive bleeding from an injury is often due to a lack of vitamin K, which is essential for the synthesis of clotting factors in the liver. Without sufficient vitamin K, the blood coagulation process is impaired, leading to increased bleeding.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>23","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : ALIMENTARY SYSTEM","question":"The diagram below is an illustration of a system in humans. Study it and answer the question      Enzymatic digestion of protein begins in the part labelled","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"I","B":"II","C":"III","D":"IV"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The enzymatic digestion of protein in man begins in the stomach.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>24","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : ALIMENTARY SYSTEM","question":"The diagram below is an illustration of a system in humans. Study it and answer the question    The parts that secrete substances involved in the digestion of fats are labelled","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"I, II and III","B":"I and III","C":"II and III","D":"I, III and IV"},"answer":"C","explanation":"the parts that secrete these substances are:    Liver    Secretes bile (stored in the gall bladder).    Bile salts emulsify fats, breaking them into tiny droplets (micelles) \u2192 increases surface area for enzymes to act.    Pancreas    Secretes pancreatic juice, which contains pancreatic lipase.    Lipase breaks down emulsified fats into fatty acids and glycerol","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>25","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : ALIMENTARY SYSTEM","question":"If the small intestine of an organism does not have villi, the organism will have a problem with","images":[],"options":{"A":"digestion of food only","B":"absorption of water","C":"absorption of nutrients only","D":"digestion of food and absorption of nutrients"},"answer":"D","explanation":"If the small intestine does not have villi, the organism will struggle with both digestion and absorption of nutrients. Villi are small, finger-like projections that increase the surface area for absorption. Without them, the efficiency of nutrient absorption is significantly reduced, impacting both digestion and nutrient uptake.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>26","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : MODES OF NUTRITION","question":"Which of the following statements is not correct about the dental formula of humans","images":[],"options":{"A":"One pair of canines is on the upper jaw and three pairs of premolars are on the lower jaw","B":"Two pairs of incisors are on the upper jaw and three pairs of premolars are on the lower jaw","C":"Two pairs of incisors are on the upper jaw and three pairs of molars are on the lower jaw","D":"One pair of canines is on the upper jaw and four pairs of molars are on the lower jaw"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The statement 'Two pairs of incisors are on the upper jaw and three pairs of premolars are on the lower jaw' is incorrect. In humans, there are typically two pairs of incisors on the upper jaw and two pairs on the lower jaw, along with two pairs of canines and two pairs of premolars on both jaws.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>27","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"ECOLOGICAL MANAGEMENT : BIOLOGICAL ASSOCIATIONS","question":"The relationship between a bean plant and a Tridax plant on a farmland is","images":[],"options":{"A":"competition","B":"predation","C":"parasitism","D":"epiphytism"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The relationship between a bean plant and a Tridax plant on farmland is one of competition. Both plants may compete for resources such as sunlight, water, and nutrients in the soil, which can affect their growth and survival.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>28","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOLOGICAL FACTORS","question":"The following ecological factors affect all habitats except","images":[],"options":{"A":"temperature","B":"humidity","C":"light","D":"pressure"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Among the listed ecological factors, pressure is not typically considered an ecological factor that affects all habitats in the same way as temperature, humidity, and light. While pressure can influence certain environments (like aquatic habitats), it is not a universal factor affecting all habitats.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>29","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : SIMPLE MEASUREMENT OF ECOLOGICAL FACTORS","question":"The diagram below is an illustration of an ecological instrument used in a habitat. Study it and answer the question      The ecological instrument is a","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"wind vane","B":"Six's thermometer","C":"Secchi disc","D":"hygrometer"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A Secchi disc is a simple scientific instrument used to measure the transparency or turbidity of water.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>30","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : SIMPLE MEASUREMENT OF ECOLOGICAL FACTORS","question":"The diagram below is an illustration of an ecological instrument used in a habitat. Study it and answer the question    The instrument is used to measure a factor","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"in the atmosphere","B":"in water","C":"on land","D":"on grasses"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The disc is lowered into the water until it just disappears from sight.  The depth at which it disappears is noted.  The disc is then slowly raised until it reappears, and this depth is also noted.  The average of these two depths is recorded as the Secchi depth.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>31","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"ECOLOGY OF POPULATION : FACTORS THAT AFFECT POPULATION","question":"When Tilapia population in a pond  reaches the carrying capacity, the population","images":[],"options":{"A":"alternately increases and decreases","B":"remains unchanged","C":"increases only","D":"decreases only"},"answer":"B","explanation":"When a population reaches its carrying capacity, it typically stabilizes and remains unchanged over time, assuming no external factors affect it. This is because the environment can support only a limited number of individuals, leading to a balance between birth and death rates.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>32","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : FOOD WEBS AND TROPHIC LEVELS","question":"Which of the following statements about the pyramid of energy is correct","images":[],"options":{"A":"Energy remains constant across trophic levels","B":"Energy decreases from the base to the apex of the pyramid","C":"Energy increases from the base to the apex of the pyramid","D":"Each trophic level is an independent energy source"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The pyramid of energy illustrates that energy decreases from the base to the apex of the pyramid. This is due to the second law of thermodynamics, which states that energy transformations are not 100% efficient, leading to energy loss at each trophic level as heat.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>33","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : NUTRIENT CYCLING IN NATURE","question":"Which of the following sequences represents the trend in eutrophication?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Heavy mineralization \u2192 lack of oxygen \u2192 massive algal growth","B":"Excessive nitrates \u2192 massive algal growth \u2192 lack of oxygen \u2192  death of aquatic organisms","C":"Excessive phosphates \u2192 lack of oxygen \u2192 massive algal growth \u2192 death of aquatic organisms","D":"Massive algal growth \u2192 excessive nitrates \u2192 lack of oxygen"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Eutrophication is a process that typically begins with excessive nutrients, such as nitrates, leading to massive algal growth. This algal bloom can deplete oxygen in the water, resulting in the death of aquatic organisms. The sequence provided in option 2 accurately represents this trend.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>34","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : POPULATION STUDIES BY SAMPLING","question":"Which of the following statements correctly describes the term population? The number of","images":[],"options":{"A":"Tilapia in a lake","B":"fungus and snail on leaf litter","C":"bees and butterflies on a flower","D":"flatworms and roundworms in the gut of an animal"},"answer":"A","explanation":"A population must be of the same species in a given habitat, while the other options describe communities (different species living together).","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>35","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : POPULATION STUDIES BY SAMPLING","question":"What is the population density of  Ageratum sp. of frequency 1,850 on a land area measuring 100m2?","images":[],"options":{"A":"18.50m2","B":"18.05m2","C":"0.50m2","D":"0.05m2"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Population density is calculated as the number of individuals per unit area. In this case, the population density of Ageratum sp. is calculated as 1850 individuals / 100 m\u00b2 = 18.50 individuals per m\u00b2. However, the options provided are in m\u00b2, which is incorrect. The correct answer should be 18.50 individuals/m\u00b2, but since none of the options correctly represent this, the answer is -1.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>36","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"MICROORGANISMS: MAN AND HEALTH : PUBLIC HEALTH","question":"Which of the following activities does not control pathogens?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Exposure to ultraviolet radiation","B":"Use of disinfectants","C":"Eating balanced diet","D":"Destroying the habitats of pathogens"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Eating a balanced diet does not directly control pathogens. While a balanced diet can support the immune system, it does not actively eliminate or control pathogens like the other options do (ultraviolet radiation, disinfectants, and destroying habitats). Therefore, the correct answer is option C.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>37","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"MICROORGANISMS: MAN AND HEALTH : PUBLIC HEALTH","question":"Which of the following diseases could be prevented by a BCG vaccination?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Malaria","B":"Cholera","C":"Tuberculosis","D":"Diphtheria"},"answer":"C","explanation":"BCG vaccination is specifically used to prevent tuberculosis (TB). It is not effective against malaria, cholera, or diphtheria.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>38","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"CONSERVATION OF NATURAL RESOURCES : WAYS OF ENSURING CONSERVATION","question":"The main effect of deforestation is","images":[],"options":{"A":"creation of new habitats","B":"loss of soil particles","C":"survival of more species","D":"reduction of carbon (IV) oxide in the atmosphere."},"answer":"B","explanation":"The main effect of deforestation is the loss of soil particles due to erosion and degradation of the land. Deforestation leads to habitat destruction, which can result in soil erosion and loss of nutrients, making it difficult for plants to grow. Therefore, the correct answer is option B.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>39","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"CONSERVATION OF NATURAL RESOURCES : WAYS OF ENSURING CONSERVATION","question":"Which of the following resources cannot be conserved?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Mineral resources","B":"Soil and water","C":"Forest and wildlife","D":"Domestic wastes"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Domestic wastes are not conserved; instead, they are reduced, reused, recycled, or disposed of.  Domestic wastes, however, are not resources in the true sense \u2014 they are by-products of human activity. While waste can be managed, recycled, or reduced, it is not something we conserve.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>40","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"CONSERVATION OF NATURAL RESOURCES : WAYS OF ENSURING CONSERVATION","question":"Which of the following activities is not suitable for forest conservation?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Felling of trees","B":"Planting seedlings","C":"Preventing bush fires","D":"Planting tree crops"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Felling of trees is not suitable for forest conservation as it leads to deforestation, which negatively impacts the ecosystem. The other options, such as planting seedlings, preventing bush fires, and planting tree crops, are all activities that contribute positively to forest conservation.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>41","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"VARIATION IN POPULATION : MORPHOLOGICAL VARIATIONS","question":"Which of the following pairs of features is an examples of discontinuous variation?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Height and blood group","B":"Height and sex","C":"Colour and weight","D":"Fingerprint and blood group"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Fingerprint and blood group are examples of discontinuous variation because they exhibit distinct categories without intermediate forms. In contrast, height and weight are continuous variations, as they can take on a range of values.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>42","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : APPLICATION OF THE PRINCIPLES OF HEREDITY","question":"The ability of some individuals to taste phenylthiocarbamide is","images":[],"options":{"A":"morphological variation","B":"physiological variation","C":"morphological adaptation","D":"physiological adaptation"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The ability to taste phenylthiocarbamide (PTC) is a physiological variation, as it relates to the biochemical processes in the body that allow some individuals to taste this compound while others cannot. This trait is genetically determined and reflects differences in sensory perception.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>43","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : CHROMOSOMES","question":"Alleles are found on","images":[],"options":{"A":"nucleus","B":"nucleolus","C":"chromosomes","D":"tissues"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Alleles are found on chromosomes. They are different forms of a gene located at specific positions (loci) on chromosomes, and they determine various traits in an organism.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>44","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : PROBABILITY IN GENETICS (HYBRID FORMATION)","question":"A couple heterozygous for albino genes have normal skin colour. What is the probability that their child would be an albino?","images":[],"options":{"A":"1/2","B":"1/3","C":"1/4","D":"1"},"answer":"C","explanation":"In a couple heterozygous for albino genes (Aa x Aa), where 'A' represents the normal skin color allele and 'a' represents the albino allele, the probability of their child being an albino (aa) is 1/4. This is derived from a Punnett square analysis of the genetic cross.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>45","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : TRANSMISSION AND EXPRESSION OF CHARACTERISTICS IN ORGANISMS","question":"The process occurring in the illustrated molecule below is","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"protein synthesis","B":"gene coding","C":"DNA replication","D":"gene mutation"},"answer":"C","explanation":"DNA Replication: Enzymes, Mechanism, Steps, Applications  DNA replication is the process by which a cell creates an identical copy of its DNA. This is crucial for cell division, ensuring each new cell receives the same genetic information as the parent cell. The process involves unwinding the double helix, separating the strands, and synthesizing new complementary strands. AI Overview  DNA Replication: Enzymes, Mechanism, Steps, Applications  DNA replication is the process by which a cell creates an identical copy of its DNA. This is crucial for cell division, ensuring each new cell receives the same genetic information as the parent cell. The process involves unwinding the double helix, separating the strands, and synthesizing new complementary strands.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>46","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : PROBABILITY IN GENETICS (HYBRID FORMATION)","question":"If the percentage of adenine in the DNA of a human is 32%, what will be the percentage of thymine?","images":[],"options":{"A":"10%","B":"16%","C":"27%","D":"32%"},"answer":"C","explanation":"In DNA, adenine (A) pairs with thymine (T). According to Chargaff's rules, the amount of adenine is equal to the amount of thymine in a double-stranded DNA molecule. Therefore, if adenine is 32%, thymine must also be 32%. However, since 32% is not an option, the closest correct answer is 27%, which is incorrect. Thus, the correct answer is not present in the options.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>47","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : LINKAGE, SEX DETERMINATION AND SEX LINKED CHARACTERS","question":"Which of the following statements is not correct about colour blindness?","images":[],"options":{"A":"it is a sex-linked trait","B":"Males are often carriers","C":"Females are not carriers","D":"The trait is controlled by a recessive gene"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Females can be carriers of color blindness, which is a sex-linked trait typically associated with the X chromosome. Males are more frequently affected because they have only one X chromosome. Therefore, the statement 'Females are not carriers' is incorrect.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>48","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"EVOLUTION : ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL","question":"Lamarck's theory of evolution states that","images":[],"options":{"A":"characteristics of organisms are not the sum of the characters of their parents","B":"characteristics of organisms are determined by mutation","C":"organisms transfer acquired characters to their offspring","D":"organisms acquire genes from their parents"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Lamarck's theory of evolution, known as Lamarckism, posits that organisms can pass on characteristics acquired during their lifetime to their offspring. This is in contrast to Darwin's theory of natural selection, which emphasizes genetic inheritance and variation. Therefore, the correct answer is that organisms transfer acquired characters to their offspring.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>49","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : BEHAVIOURAL ADAPTATIONS IN SOCIAL ANIMALS.","question":"The castes of the organisms found in a beehive are","images":[],"options":{"A":"drones, queen and workers","B":"workers, soldiers and reproductives","C":"soldiers, workers and king","D":"king, queen and soldiers"},"answer":"A","explanation":"In a beehive, the castes of the organisms are drones, the queen, and workers. Drones are male bees, the queen is the reproductive female, and workers are non-reproductive females that perform various tasks in the hive. Therefore, the correct answer is 'drones, queen and workers'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2025>50","subject":"Biology","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"EVOLUTION : ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL","question":"The theory of natural selection in evolution was formulated by","images":[],"options":{"A":"Mathias Schleiden","B":"Louis Pasteur","C":"Charles Darwin","D":"Jean Lamarck"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The theory of natural selection was formulated by Charles Darwin. He proposed that organisms better adapted to their environment tend to survive and produce more offspring. This concept is a fundamental principle of evolutionary biology. Therefore, the correct answer is 'Charles Darwin'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"}];